//@ compile-fail
//@ error-contains: is sealed

// `sealed` is `opaque` plus a trust boundary: outsiders may not ASSERT the type out of an
// erased value. An assertion is either redundant -- the holder could test with `is`/`as?`
// -- or it is the mistake `sealed` exists to make unrepresentable: claiming unconditional
// knowledge of a capability type. The testing forms stay legal and are pinned in
// sealed_recovery_by_test.neon.
//
// Construction protection is NOT what this adds -- every forge route is already dead under
// plain `opaque` (the structural gates statically, the canonical tag check at runtime).
// What `as!` would assert here can only ever be a value `vault` really built; the ban is
// about where the failure lands: a compile error naming the owner, not a disclosed trap in
// production.

use std::io;

internal mod vault {
    sealed record Secret { code: i64 }
    fn seal(n: i64) -> Secret { Secret { code: n } }
    fn value(s: Secret) -> i64 { s.code }
}

fn main() {
    let a: any = vault::seal(7);
    let s = a as! vault::Secret;
    io::println(to_string(vault::value(s)));
}
